**Clinical Reasoning:**
Pilocarpine acts on the sphincter pupillae to induce miosis (pupillary constriction) by stimulating muscarinic receptors. Similarly, tropicamide acts as a muscarinic antagonist, preventing acetylcholine from activating the sphincter pupillae, thereby allowing the dilator pupillae (sympathetically driven) to dominate and cause pupil dilation. While their direct actions differ—pilocarpine stimulates constriction versus tropicamide blocks constriction—their mechanism of action on opposing components of the pupillary apparatus creates functional analogs: pilocarpine activates the sphincter pupillae, and tropicamide indirectly allows the dilator pupillae to function uninhibited. Thus, tropicamide’s inhibition of the sphincter pupillae parallels pilocarpine’s stimulation of it in terms of targeting the same muscular pathway. Among listed choices, only tropicamide shares this interaction with the pupillary sphincter via antagonism.

